I like the core idea of this article. The entity itself is very interesting, between its behavior, overall concept, and an innovative method of killing. The execution half does and half doesn't meet the idea; the formatting and visuals make the article engaging, but the writing can be clunky at times, with semi-frequent grammatical errors and lapses in tone.

In general, the article leaves the reader with a good balance of answers and questions, but also contains contradictions on the nature of the entity described and leaves some things unacknowledged that really ought to be. For example, its method of killing is interesting, but why does it kill in the first place? The use of the word  to describe this process implies this is a form of feeding, but there seems to be no inquiry to this end at all. In addition, it's that SCP-5927 is unable to interact with physical objects not covered in light-absorbent paint, but is shown in Addendum-5927-4 to physically fling and tear apart field agents. I would assume it was using the agents' protective equipment to do so, assuming the incident takes place after Experiment 5927-6, except that it's explicitly stated to have carried out these actions by skewering agents with its appendages and retracting its appendages quickly from an agent, respectively.

Overall, I would say this is a good article that could use polishing. +1







